AB  - The celebrated end of Apartheid did not resolve all intergroup tensions in South Africa. In particular, newcomers have become a target of intergroup hostility and are generally perceived as threatening by citizens. Whereas the tendency for citizens to dislike newcomers has been extensively documented, citizens' support for newcomers' fundamental rights have received less attention. The present study examines Black and White South African citizens' attitudes toward newcomers' rights and how these might be improved. Specifically, we examine whether the usual benefits of contact for improving intergroup relations are undermined when newcomers are perceived as highly threatening. Results indicate that representative samples of Black (n = 2496) and White (n = 458) South Africans do not support the rights of newcomers to the same degree that they support the rights of South African citizens. Also, citizens who have more contact with newcomers report higher support for newcomers' rights when they did not perceive that newcomers posed high realistic or numeric threat. However, contact is no longer associated with increased support for newcomers' rights in the presence of high realistic threat for Black citizens; whereas for White citizens, contact is no longer associated with increased support for newcomers' rights in the presence of high numeric threat. © 2016 American Psychological Association.
